[[File:ISS27 Catherine Coleman plays a flute.jpg|thumb|[[NASA]] astronaut [[Catherine Coleman]] plays a flute aboard the [[International Space Station]] in 2011.]] '''Music in space''' is [[music]] played in or broadcast from a [[spacecraft]] in [[outer space]].<ref name="sciencemuseum">{{cite web|url=http://www.sciencemuseum.org.uk/visitmuseum/Plan_your_visit/exhibitions/cosmonauts/life-in-space/tuned-in-music-of-the-soviet-space-programme|publisher=sciencemuseum.org.uk|title=Tuned in: music of the Soviet space programme|accessdate=November 4, 2016}}</ref>{{Failed verification|reason=Article says nothing at all about unmanned missions.|date=November 2016}} According to the [[Smithsonian Institution]], the first musical instruments played in outer space were an 8-note [[Hohner]] "Little Lady" [[harmonica]] and a handful of small bells carried by American astronauts [[Wally Schirra]] and [[Thomas P. Stafford]] aboard [[Gemini 6A]].<ref name="Smithsonian Mag 2005">{{cite web|last1=Edwards|first1=Owen|title=The Day Two Astronauts Said They Saw a UFO Wearing a Red Suit|url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/day-two-astronauts-said-they-saw-ufo-santa-suit-109444898/|website=Smithsonian Magazine|publisher=The Smithsonian Institution|accessdate=June 23, 2017|language=en|date=2005}}</ref> Upon achieving a [[space rendezvous]] in Earth orbit with their sister ship [[Gemini 7]] in December 1965, Schirra and Stafford played a rendition of "[[Jingle Bells]]" over the radio after jokingly claiming to have seen an [[unidentified flying object]] piloted by [[Santa Claus]]. The instruments had been [[List of objects smuggled into space|smuggled]] on-board without NASA's knowledge, leading [[Mission Control]] director [[Elliot See]] to exclaim "You're too much" to Schirra after the song.<ref name="Smithsonian Mag 2005" /> The harmonica was donated to the Smithsonian by Schirra in 1967, with his note that it "...plays quite well".<ref name="Harmonica, Gemini 6">{{cite web|url=https://airandspace.si.edu/collection-objects/harmonica-gemini-6|title=Harmonica, Gemini 6|date=20 March 2016|publisher=}}</ref>
In the 1970s music tape cassettes were brought to the American space station [[Skylab]],<ref>[http://www.armaghplanet.com/blog/skylab-everything-you-need-to-know.html]</ref> while Soviet cosmonauts [[Aleksandr Laveikin]] and [[Yuri Romanenko]] brought a guitar to the space station ''[[Mir]]'' in 1987.<ref name="sciencemuseum"/> Musical instruments must be checked for gases they may emit before being taken aboard the confined environment of a space station.<ref name="space station music nasasci">{{cite web|url=http://science1.nasa.gov/science-news/science-at-nasa/2003/04sep_music/|title=Space Station Music|work=NASA Science News|publisher=NASA|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111026163708/http://science1.nasa.gov/science-news/science-at-nasa/2003/04sep_music/|archivedate=October 26, 2011|date=September 4, 2003}}</ref> As of 2003, instruments that have been aboard the [[International Space Station]] include a flute, a [[keytar|keyboard guitar]], a saxophone, and a [[didgeridoo]].<ref name="space station music nasasci"/>
Music in space has been a focal point of public relation events of various [[human spaceflight]] programs.<ref name="sciencemuseum"/> [[NASA]] astronaut [[Carl Walz]] played a rendition of the [[Elvis Presley]] song "[[Heartbreak Hotel]]" aboard the ISS in 2003 which was also recorded and transmitted to Earth.<ref name="space station music nasasci"/> [[Canadian Space Agency]] astronaut [[Chris Hadfield]], commander of [[Expedition 35]] to the [[International Space Station]], recorded a [[music video]] of the song "[[Space Oddity]]" by [[David Bowie]] aboard the space station. The first music video ever shot in space,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://io9.com/chris-hadfield-sings-space-oddity-in-the-first-music-503764317|last=Davis|first=Lauren|title=Chris Hadfield sings "Space Oddity" in the first music video in space|date=12 May 2013|publisher=[[Gawker Media]]|accessdate=29 May 2013}}</ref> the video went [[Viral video|viral]] and received widespread international media coverage after being posted to [[YouTube]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Knapp|first=Alex|title=Astronaut Chris Hadfield Sings David Bowie As He Departs The International Space Station|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alexknapp/2013/05/13/astronaut-chris-hadfield-sings-david-bowie-as-he-departs-the-international-space-station/|newspaper=[[Forbes]]|date=13 May 2013|accessdate=29 May 2013}}</ref> Bowie himself later called the cover "possibly the most poignant version of the song ever created".<ref>{{cite news|author=Andrew Griffin |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/david-bowie-how-chris-hadfield-space-oddity-cover-from-orbit-was-helped-by-the-real-starman-a6805586.html |title=David Bowie: How Chris Hadfield's 'Space Oddity' cover from orbit was helped by the 'Starman' |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |date= |accessdate=2016-10-02}}</ref>
==Dongfanghong I== {{see also|Dong Fang Hong I}} '''''Dongfanghong I''''' ({{zh|s=‰∏úÊñπÁ∫¢‰∏ÄÂè∑|t=Êù±ÊñπÁ¥Ö‰∏ÄËôü|p=D≈çngfƒÅngh√≥ng Yƒ´h√†o|l=The East is Red 1}}) was the [[People's Republic of China]]'s first space [[satellite]], launched successfully on 24 April 1970 as part of the PRC's [[Dong Fang Hong|Dongfanghong]] space satellite program. The satellite carried a [[radio transmitter]] which broadcast the song of the same name, ''D≈çngfƒÅngh√≥ng'' or "[[The East Is Red (song)|The East Is Red]]"; the broadcast lasted for 20 days while in orbit.
==Apollo 17== {{see also|Apollo 17}} A few bars of "The Fountain in the Park" were sung on the [[Moon]] by [[NASA]] Astronauts [[Harrison Schmitt]] and [[Eugene Cernan]] on the 1972 [[Apollo 17]] mission. Schmitt started by singing "I was strolling on the Moon one day..." when Cernan joined in. Cernan kept with the original "merry month of May", however, while Schmitt sang "December", which was the actual date at the time. After a brief debate, Schmitt resumed, singing "When much to my surprise, a pair of bonny eyes..." until he could no longer remember the lyrics and began vocalizing the notes instead.<ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://history.msfc.nasa.gov/saturn_apollo/videos.html |title=Astronauts Strolling on Moon and Singing |date=December 1972 |type=Videotape |publisher=NASA}}</ref> Moments later, [[Capsule communicator#Capsule Communicator|Capsule Communicator]] [[Robert A. Parker]] cut in from [[Christopher C. Kraft Jr. Mission Control Center|Houston]], saying "sorry about that, guys, but today may be December."{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}
==Voyager Golden Record== {{main article|Contents of the Voyager Golden Record}} The [[Voyager program]] probes ''[[Voyager 1]]'' and ''[[Voyager 2]]'' which by 2016 were still the [[List of artificial objects escaping from the Solar System|farthest human made object]] from [[Earth]] (also ''Voyager 1'' is reported to have reached interstellar space) where the [[Interstellar medium|galactic plasma]] is present.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/voyager/voyager20130912.html|title = NASA Spacecraft Embarks on Historic Journey Into Interstellar Space|date = September 12, 2013|website = nasa.gov|publisher = NASA|accessdate = April 15, 2014}}</ref> ''Voyager 1'' and ''Voyager 2'' were launched by [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration|NASA]] with a message aboard ‚Äî a kind of [[time capsule]], intended to communicate to extraterrestrials a story of the world of [[human]]s on Earth.<ref name="vgr">{{Cite web|url=http://voyager.jpl.nasa.gov/spacecraft/goldenrec.html|title=Voyager ‚Äì Golden Record|publisher=[[NASA]]accessdate= September 23, 2010}}</ref>
{{quote|This is a present from a small, distant world, a token of our sounds, our science, our images, our music, our thoughts and our feelings. We are attempting to survive our time so we may live into yours. |[[President of the United States|President]] [[Jimmy Carter]]}}
Audio sections contain the spoken greetings in the remaining four languages, including [[Esperanto language|Esperanto]] and [[!Kung language|!Kung]], and also whale sounds were provided by [[Roger Payne]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Gambino |first=Megan |title=What Is on Voyager's Golden Record? |url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/science-nature/What-Is-on-Voyagers-Golden-Record.html |publisher=Smithsonian Magazine |date=April 23, 2012 |accessdate=November 19, 2012}}</ref> The next audio section is devoted to the "sounds of Earth" that include:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://voyager.jpl.nasa.gov/spacecraft/sounds.html|title=Voyager ‚Äì Spacecraft ‚Äì Golden Record ‚Äì Sounds of Earth|accessdate=August 17, 2008|publisher=[[NASA]]}}</ref> {{Col-begin}} {{Col-break}} * "Music of the Spheres" ‚Äì [[Johannes Kepler]]'s "[[Harmonices Mundi]]" realized by [[Laurie Spiegel]] * [[Volcano]]es, [[Earthquake]], [[Thunder]] * [[Mudpot|Mud Pots]] * [[Wind]], [[Rain]], [[wikt:surf|Surf]] * [[Cricket (insect)|Crickets]], [[Frog]]s * [[Bird]]s, [[Hyena]], [[Elephant]], [[Whale]] * [[Chimpanzee]] * [[Wind]] * [[Wild Dog]] * Footsteps, [[Cardiac cycle|Heartbeat]], [[Laughter]] * The First Tools {{Col-break}} * Tame [[Dog]] * [[Herding]] [[Sheep]], [[Blacksmith]], [[Saw]]ing * [[Tractor]], [[Rivet]]er * [[Morse Code]], Ships (precisely, a ship's [[Horn (acoustic)|horn]]) * [[Horse]] and [[Cart]] * [[Train]] * [[Tractor]], [[Bus]], [[Automobile|Auto]] * [[F-111]] Flyby, [[Saturn V]] Lift-off * [[Kiss]], Mother and Child * Life Signs, [[Pulsar]] {{Col-end}}
Included within the "Sounds of Earth" audio portion of the Golden Record is a track containing the inspirational message ''[[per aspera ad astra]]'' in [[Morse Code]]. Translated from Latin, it means, "through hardships to the stars".
==''Beagle 2'' and Blur== In 2003 the British space organization's ''[[Beagle 2]]'' probe was scheduled to play a song from the UK music band Blur, upon touchdown on the planet [[Mars]].<ref name="theverge">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/1/16/7555809/beagle-2-blur-melody-mars|publisher=theverge.com|title=Listen to the music that the Beagle 2 probably played on Mars in 2003 - The Verge|accessdate=November 4, 2016}}</ref> It was not known what happened to ''Beagle 2'' for 11 years after landing, and it was considered lost. When it was found intact in 2015, however, the possibility was raised that ''Beagle 2'' had successfully played the song on Christmas Day in 2003 upon landing, but failed to transmit back to Earth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/1/16/7555809/beagle-2-blur-melody-mars|title=Listen to the music that the Beagle 2 probably played on Mars in 2003|first=James|last=Vincent|date=16 January 2015|publisher=}}</ref>
==''Curiosity'' rover and Reach for the Stars== {{main article|Reach for the Stars (will.i.am song)}} American recording artist [[will.i.am]] wrote, produced, and recorded the song "Reach for the Stars" (alternately subtitled "Mars Edition" and "NASA Edition") in commemoration of the landing of the [[Curiosity rover|''Curiosity'' rover]] on Mars. The song was first released on August 28, 2012, and it became the first song that was successfully broadcast from another planet.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/08/29/us/mars-single/index.html?hpt=hp_c2 |title=Will.i.am premieres song -- from Mars |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=August 29, 2012 |accessdate=January 25, 2014 |last=Karimi |first=Faith}}</ref>
==Elon Musk's Tesla Roadster== [[File:Elon Musk's Tesla Roadster (40110297852).jpg|thumb|"Starman" prop rocks out to Bowie en route to the Asteroid belt]] {{main|Elon Musk's Tesla Roadster}} Elon Musk's Tesla Roadster was launched into Earth orbit, then Solar orbit, in February 2018 as part of the [[Falcon Heavy Test Flight]]. The sound system on board the car was looping the Bowie songs "[[Space Oddity]]" and "[[Life on Mars?]]".<ref>{{cite web|title=SpaceX Successfully Launches the Falcon Heavy‚ÄîAnd Elon Musk's Roadster|url=https://www.wired.com/story/spacex-successfully-launches-the-falcon-heavyand-elon-musks-roadster/|website=WIRED|accessdate=7 February 2018}}</ref>
